"smart_sources:000 Zettelkasten/The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient..md": {"path":"000 Zettelkasten/The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient..md","class_name":"SmartSource","history":[{"blocks":{"000 Zettelkasten/The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient..md#":true,"000 Zettelkasten/The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient..md#The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient. Two inhibitory signals targeted for this method are CTLA-4 and PDL-1. Clinical trials that have incorporated these immunotherapy targets have observed success in boosting T-cell activity towards viral and tumour antigens.{1}":true,"000 Zettelkasten/The split-receptor method helps to maintain CART-T specificity by using a negative feedback signaling to prevent excessive T-cell activity and minimize proinflammatory damage to the patient..md#References":true},"mtime":1709479657478,"size":634,"hash":"95c7960f56d416c66049951961aec2981097f9dd5f9e2f00c3af4a64e7b01c03"}],"embeddings":{"TaylorAI/bge-micro-v2":{"vec":[-0.01364081,-0.00507365,-0.02176514,0.03561501,0.04216611,-0.01162192,0.00726062,-0.02897201,-0.00805609,0.00186606,-0.01011201,-0.00584821,-0.02814073,-0.04547573,0.02034431,-0.0016241,0.02643144,-0.01383225,0.01623874,-0.00949479,0.06519098,-0.00766707,-0.003555